w
onderful constitution he said you were well fed when you were a child. It is - he felt my arms - he said you were well fed when you were a child. I said we were - oh yes, there was nothing - we were never short of anything - we weren't - well no one got s
uch in the way of wages that time and I know dad's wages on the Met. - well I don't think - he'd have two fifteen might have been three pound a week - it wasn't any more.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did you have anything-different on Sundays for Breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh I couldn't tel
l you - that I couldn't tell you now. What we - I know we were always well fed and there was always a good joint and I remember my brother Frank once saying - er - he was very fond of tapioca pudding - and of course there's always eggs went in tapioca pud
d
ing - yes - and on this table mother had put this very big dish of tapioca and - er - yes, mum - a little bit more please mum - he says you know mum - I was there - he said why make it in a dish like that he said I - I think we might make a bucket full an
d done with it. Mother said oh we couldn't make a pudding in a bucket because you couldn't put it in the oven.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Apart from the grapes did your mother or father grow any other fruit or veg?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh no, no. We hadn't got the - hadn't got the space no. We just had our little back garden - mother looked after.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did they buy fresh fruit and vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Yes, plenty of it. Plenty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 And tinned fruit and vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Er - no - not so much - because - er - you couldn't buy it in those days, oh 
no, you - er - no you wouldn't be buying anything you know, and we always had the best of tea, sugar - so to speak which was of course cheap and butter and I know that our butter always came from the Home and Colonial in Edgware Road - the tea and the but
ter - dad always used to bring that home - as he came home on Friday evening - always.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did they keep any livestock for the family - hens or pigs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh - er - pigs? Oh - they didn't get pigs out here - not here - no - chickens we had - out in the garden.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Do you remember how often a week you had meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Pretty well every day - I think so anyway. If we didn't have meat we had .....
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did you ever have tinned meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 No, we never had anything in tins. No, my dad wouldn't have anything in
 tins. And it was a great deal of annoyance to him when someone - er - when margarine first came out and - they said well it was cooking butter and I know I had occasion to - er - to ask someone - I think it was the milk shop - I think they - a little mil
k
 shop was there then - or it could have been in the Home and Colonial I said well look bring me up some margarine and I'll make some cakes - rock cakes. Dad said no you won't - you won't make them with margarine, he said, you'll have the butter - I don't 
want margarine - I don't like it - we don't order that cooking fat and he wouldn't have it - he wouldn't have it in the house. Of course it wasn't purified like it is today - oh good gracious no.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did you ever get some extra meat such as rabbit from poaching?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Er - no, poaching - eh - poaching - oh no thank you. Oh no. Not - er - now - not in poaching - oh no, definitely not but I had a cousin who was - um - ah - pff - Harry Burrows his name was - he was - not gamekeeper but - er - something just a
 little bit above the head of Sir Walter Gilbey down at Bishops Stortford and when they went shooting he had - not in - not in our younger days - oh no - but in our older days - Harry used to send up a pair of rabbits or a hare - they'd come up you know w
i
th a label tied round his neck. Oh yes. That's - er - off the estate - when they were on the estate and he unfortunately was killed in 1926 - that young man. No, he used to come and see us now and again - um - in 1926 when we had the - what I was trying t
o
 get out but I couldn't get it. It was a general strike - he had been up to town and was just going back to Elsenham - that was the name of the place - outside Bishops Stortford - he was just going back to Elsenham and he was with friends in the railway c
a
rriage as it drew into the station he went to get out and another train was hard on it - they were being driven by any Tom, Dick and Harry - and it smashed into it - he just had time to shout to the people that were in the train - get out the other side a
s
 the station roof came down and killed him. He didn't - didn't save his life - and he was - his widow was the first railway accident that had come out from the - um - Daily Mail I think it was - that had an insurance for railway accidents and it - and tha
t accident was the first one of a railway - 'cos it was in the paper - quite a lot - quite a lot about it in the paper at the time - Harry Burrows. That - that was - er - dad's - er - eldest sister's son.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Do you ever remember seeing your mother having less food than the rest of you so that the family could have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Less food? No, no, no thank you - no - there was never any occasion for anything like that. Oh no, no occasion.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did your father have more food than the rest of the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Oh, I don't ask me - he had what was needed - oh no. One thing I do remember - that on Saturday mornings - I was the youngest one and my sister and brother - George - used to go through Shirland Road to what is now the United Dairies on Saturday morning -
 
it was then Wellfords - because Wellfords were our milkman - but they didn't bring this skimmed milk round for puddings - not - you had your - you had your pint can or whatever you had - which had to be washed and put out - doors - out on the step at nigh
t
 - a pint or two pints or whatever you had but - er - this was a big can with a top to it and they used to take it and a jug up to the corner of Eldon Avenue for skimmed milk which was then sold at tuppence half penny a quart - yes - and they used to carr
y
 it all the way down Shirland Road and round the Avenue to the house to make milk puddings. But in due course we had a milkman who is Sutlands at the corner of - er - Caird Street - er - it was this Mr Sutland's father - er - they opened a - and how ordin
ary milk is today. Oh yes, every bit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Were you allowed to talk during meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Mmm - I don't think that dad was very - my dad was not strict. You couldn't call him a Strict man - oh no - he wasn't a - he wasn't - er - he looked upon his sons and da
ughters as having sufficient intelligence that they could talk. I don't say that - I don't say that there was an - much conversation but - er - I don't know that they were - hindered at all. Oh no, no my dad wasn't strict at all - in fact he was too lenie
nt I think - with all of us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Could you choose what you wanted to eat from what was cooked or did you have to eat a bit of everything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh, I don't know. No, I don't think so. Oh I think we did - we did the - average feeding as you would do in thos
e days. As I say, we were well fed. Thoroughly well fed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Say you wanted salt or something like that - you could ask somebody to pass it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh, yes, yes. Oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 You didn't have to wait until it was offered to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh, well no, no. Oh no, we just lived as .....
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 And you could ask for a second helping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Yes, you would. I told you my brother Frank said well mum why don't you make it in a pail.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Were you expected to sit in a certain way and hold your knife and fork in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Er - well, I think we were well brought up - er - but we didn't get to the - to the - um - state of serviettes - we had - no - we were a homely family but we didn't come to the state of serviettes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Could you bring toys or a book to the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Er - well, I don't know - I don't know that we ever did that - no, I think when we'd finished eating - er - we all got down and I remember our kitchen table had a wide leaf to it - and we had a box up at the other end well - sort of little ottoma
n - it was up that end at the far wall and then - er - be it Nellie - I don't know who'd sit beside her - until after - until after her young man came along - er - I don't know when they would say it - with the two boys up that end.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 You always sat down together did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Always sat down together - oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 And you always sat in the same places?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh yes, we all had our same places - yes. I used to sit beside me mother. Mother and dad in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Who served the meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Mother. Mother always served the meals - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did she serve you in any special order?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Oh I don't know - they don't - oh I don't know quite. In that respect really. But she would - um - we - we behaved ourselves as young people. I was the youngest - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Can you remember how you used to sit before you were old enough to sit at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Yes. On a - I had my little stool on one side of the fireplace and George the other - when we had our porridge. Always had our porridge sitting on that - er - t
hose - him one side of the fireplace and me the other - we had - we had little low stools - oh yes, and those stools went under the table when they were finished with - oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Before you were old enough to feed yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh I don't know about that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 As soon as you were old enough you joined in the family meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
We were all in the family - oh yes. That would be by the time - as I say - I'd be coming here and we come in here I would be ten - I would be ten years old then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Was your mother an easy person to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 She was a lovely little woman. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 She'd show you affection?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Wait a minute - where are you - where are you mum and dad - they're down here somewhere - because I had a photo - look at that - in that box
 under there - wait a minute - if I can find that - I've just remembered I - I know I had them up - oh - don't you go over as well - that's it dear - put them out of sight - out of sight - out of mind - well, I know I've got to put them out - back into a 
frame.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Was your mother an easy person to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Yes. She was a good soul too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 And she showed you affection?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 To anybody - yes - wonderful - and she .....
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 If you had any worries could you share them with her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh yes. Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 And was your father an easy person to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 He was very easy - he was too lenient really - in a way but - er - he was fond of all his family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 He showed affection?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Yes, yes. We were a happy family all together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 And you could go to him if you had any worries?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Yes, he was - oh yes, if you had anything troubling you - oh yes. Oh every - where - all the way through really - right until he died.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 How did your parents expect you to behave towards them - did they have any special way to address them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 No, oh no. No. No, they were mum and dad to us all the way through.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 And did they bring you up to behave towards your brothers and sisters in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 No. No. Just the - to realize you were all brothers an
d sisters and it was an open house - this was always an open house for anyone who - er - of - er - friends of my brothers or - we had friends home and boyfriends and girlfriends for that matter and - er - my eldest brother eventually }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16328850 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508  his cousin and
 - er - and his - their daughter - their eldest daughter - er - had been down to Leicester with me - she lives at Waddensdale and - but what I was going to say - oh it's gone - er - they - er - oh the - dad never barred anyone of coming to the house, I me
a
n to say, he'd always make them welcome - no matter who they were - boys or girls and we had - er - four cousins and one of mother's sisters doing service up in Hampstead - all four - all four of these sisters - their home was at Royden - in Essex - and t
h
ey always made this their home if they were out of a job - er - there was always somewhere to sleep them somewhere or other - - er - oh in the little chairs that we used to let down and - or something like that - er - if one or the other of them would kip
 
down in if we - if it were needed but it was very seldom that anything like that. But these girls used to come over from Hampstead - the four sisters - in - er - one was parlourmaid to - er - to Sir Roland Hill's brother - one and the one my brother Alfre
d }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16328850 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
 - my sister-in-law - Lizzie - er - who was also my cousin - er - she was at - er - she was in service in Barnsbury you see - but they always used to make this - er - Sunday afternoons or all day Sundays or if it was a holiday time they always come
 - always used to come and see us - oh yes - we were a united family - the whole way through really. But - er - you never had any quarrels or any troubles and I don't know that any of us got into any scrapes we certainly never - certainly no one got into 
any - er - serious trouble - any police court troubles or anything like that - oh no - that was - 'course that would have been tragic. Ooh - gracious no.
