\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 When you were small did your parents say that if any child to hit you to hit back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 No, we d
idn't - no not in those days - they do now though don't they - oh yes. You hit him back - go on - he hit you. They had - there was - I don't think we ever quarreled in that way because we girls used to - the girls used to play together and the boys used t
o play together - they'd be spinning their tops or running their hoops round and that - oh yes, life was so different in those days. To what it is - has been of late years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 What kind of people do you think your parents hoped you would grow up to be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Well, my sister was supposed to have - I told you she went as a court dressmaker - but - um - my father's - one of my father's sisters was - um - manageress of Borwicks Baking Powder and she'd got - was one of those very - you know - prim and proper ol
d dears and - er - oh when Ellen - she always used to call my sister Ellen - when Ellen - er - grows up I want her to be a ladies maid - mm - my beloved sister says I'm not going to be any ladies maid, mum. She paid I want to go into dressmaking. And of c
ourse she did. She stayed in it the court - at - er - this place in Packer Street until she was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16328850 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did your parents bring you up to consider certain things important in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 An outline of life? Well, I don't know that they did that much be
cause it wasn't done so much - er - there was certain things that were not revealed to us in our days - fact - well youngsters talk about when they're five years old these days - but - oh no - things were kept very private - in many ways. But you learnt m
o
re when you got older and you got out into the world and mixed with other people, whatever you did really at home - which - perhaps it was best - perhaps it wasn't I feel - I'm not too sure about it. Now if you look a - er - well of course life at that ti
m
e - when we were growing up - life was - you lived a sheltered life. You went to church and Sunday - you went to Sunday school and you'd go to church in the evening. Then if you - it was summertime with his frock coat and silk hat - oh yes - and mother wi
th her - er - silk cape and that you know and little bonnet and now of course things are so different. I never - never had a photo of - I don't think I ever had a photo of mother taken with her - er - bonnet and cape - don't think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 What did your parents think of swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
No. You never - you never heard - no, I never heard even use the word damn. No, not until - you didn't know it - you didn't know those - er - any bad language much less carry on anything that was - no, no you were bought up in
 a quiet - I wouldn't say sanctimonious - no - but - er - in a quiet way of living - the whole way through.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 When grown ups were talking were you allowed to join in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Er - well I couldn't tell you that exactly. I don't know that there was much con
versation with the grown ups that for - because I think the too away - well you see there was so much difference between the three older ones than there was between George and I.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 If you did something your parents disapproved of what would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 You might get a smack then - I don't say you didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 And who would usually give it to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh mother. Oh def - my - my dad never did lay a hand on me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Or any of your brothers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 No. I think Frank once got into trouble because he'd got
 a new suit on and he went down to the canal and - er - I don't know whether he got mucked up or he fell in the canal or whatever it was but it was something to do with Hamal canal I remember. I know he - I think dad read the riot act a little bit to him 
when he got back. But that was when I was quite a tiny little thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Was it often you got punished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh no, no, I never - and I never remember mother - she might have kept a cane but I never remember her using a cane at any time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Do you remember any particular occasion when you were punished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Er - no, I can't say that I do really - they were too lenient I think really and truly it would have been better perhaps if we had been more - but I don't think there was any need for it - I don't 
think in those days - that you lived under the threat of punishment really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Would you say that you received the ideas you had about how to behave from both your parents or did one play a more important part than the other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 No, no, both. Both my 
parents - yes. In the fam - my dad made - he certainly made a fuss of me - er - and - well not many years ago - my sister and I would be sitting in there - in the next room - just before she died - if I was a little - er - cantankerous - er - she'd say - 
you always were a spoilt kid. You, you - well, I say I was born on my father's birthday I was entitled to be. You always were a spoilt kid.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 When you had a birthday would it be different from any other day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Yes, there was always a birthday cake.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did you receive any presents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Oh yes, there was always something from someone or the other of them - er - you know - in the home - oh yes, we always - there was always - little presents - little things that would be useful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did you have any friends in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Well, when we were children we did - oh yes. Er - and I remember my next door neighbour that was then - not just now - but was then - er - she always used to come in to my birthday party and I would then make what - I would make at the sc
hool cookery which would be rock cake - that was one thing we were very particular about - was the rock cakes - but - er - we always kept up our birthdays up to a certain extent.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Can you remember anything you did with your mother and father together on Christmas day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Oh we always made a Christmas day of it - here - yes. Mother would be making the pastry and mince pies in the next room with the kitchen fire - er - an open grate - with the kitchen fire and then father would be over night putting up
 all the decorations - 'course he had some pictures on the wall those days. I might tell you my - my looking glass isn't - it's down there at the present minute - under that big cushion - er - why that isn't up - it's there until the men have - they have 
practically finished now out here with that drill and - er - so I'm waiting for them to be quite finished and then I'll get one or the other of them to put it up for me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 So you had a good Christmas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh yes. We always had - and - of course we had 
brass - a big brass lamp - I don't whether that big lamp - er - used to stand. Might be - might have been in the middle of the table because we had a big round table here - and - yes, it possibly would stand on that - er - for the time when that was aligh
t
 - um - that would be put out when my father would have the biggest dish we'd got - what we called the turkey dish - with - er - yes - what did we call it - snapdragons. Which would be raisins that you would buy in those days for about - er - well tuppenc
e
 threepence a pound quite likely - er - quite a small amount and - er - I don't know what spirit he used - I think it was whisky - it had - er - they had to set those alight and they - they were what they called snapdragons - the older people would rememb
e
r them - snapdragons - and - er - my brother George was such a strong teetotaler that he always used to take a hand - he used to take a handful with the - the glow on them and go and put them under the tap and wash the whisk - and wash the spirit off them
.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 They were soaked in whisky and then set light to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Yes, they would soak in whisky and then set light to. Did you ever have them? Didn't you? Didn't you ever - oh yes, our snapdragons - yes - on Christmas night - towards the end of Christmas nig
ht after all the bon-bons and - er - presents had been taken off the tree - and we had a tree - there'd be presents taken off the tree and a little bit of something for everybody. Even to the cat - yes - 'cos we had a cat in those days and - er - there wo
u
ld be - er - presents there that would be going out to aunts and uncles - those that were probably not able to be present and we always had a turkey - during the time he was - dad was on the Metropolitan Railway he always a big turkey and we used - my bro
t
her George and I used to go down to meet him at Edgware Road station and in the - one of the booking office - one of the offices - on Edgware Road station - er - on the level - er - we used to meet dad there because it - that was where he was going to pic
k
 up his turkey and it isn't only in recent years that the nail that that turkey used to hang on over the fireplace in the scullery has been taken down. It's only been in quite recent years - I don't know why it was taken down even then but - er - it was, 
b
ecause I know I looked for it one day and I said Oh lor' my big nails gone - now after all these years and then of course - I don't know how that turkey would be cooked - it must have been cooked in the kitchen oven - must you know because we hadn't got g
a
s. Oh possibly - no - no, we didn't have gas until - we had a - a little bungalow stove was the first one and that wasn't in until about - um - 19 - 93 - 94 - 95 - about 1895 to 96 I think when we had gas because I remember my dad was very ill in 1893 and
 when he was better during the winter time - er - and that\rquote 
s what he got - he got pneumonia through - er - spouting I was going to say - er - for the benefit of Mr Hornerman - er - our - er - er - Liberal candidate that was. He used to stand at the door - d
oor and mother used to say to him, now look here, you'll get pneumonia one of these days. And of course poor old dad did - but still he got over it and while - was going to tell you that - he would sit at this window during the January or February when th
e
 - when the ice was very bad on the ground and see the gas people laying the gas that was coming into our houses - er - and our next door neighbour in 44 were the first people that had it - I think the first in the street - the first in the immediate neig
h
bourhood and dad was very - er - inter - er - enthusiastic about it - oh he said must go in and see Mrs Page when - when I'm better - when they get that gas fitted up - and too, I think we must have the gas - we'll see - if it's all right. And of course w
e
 did - the pipe used to come across and under here up here and one bracket would be there and the other pipe - er - from it would go along the mantlepiece and up there into the other bracket - when they had - where we had - er - glass - er - red and white
 
sort of globes that were screwed on and then you had - er - oh I think at the first it was like a fan shape - the original - yes a little twiddly bit about like that and a fan shape - then afterwards it got to be the incandescent light - little radiant in
candescent bulbs that if you didn't watch out what you were doing - you dropped the lot and then that one went bang and eventually it was taken away - it was taken away from the fireplace but - put in the middle of the room from over here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did you have any musical instruments in the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Er - we had a harmonium. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 And who used to play it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Dad. Oh dad. My dad could. And he could play his concertina. I think I told you about his concertina didn't I.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did any of you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Er - no - but we used to stand all round and sing. Oh yes. And mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 You all used to sing?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh yes, when we were younger.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 When would you do this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 This would be Sunday evenings. Sunday evening after church - oh yes. Yes, oh yes, singing together - had a singing lesson very often.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did your parents play any games with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Er - not to a great degree. No, I don't know that they did up to - no, and cards - ordinary cards were forbidden up to a point. At least, I won't say forbidden - n
o, but we never looked for them. And yet, when my aunt from Australia - er - one of mother's sisters that went out to Australia - when she came back here - dad used to come in and keep her company - because she came and lived with us for a little while - 
er - after the boys were all }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16328850 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
 and that - um - she came to live with us until she went back to Australia - when she was seventy-nine - and - er - that's where she died - um - er - my dad would come in and play a game of cards with - er - with aunt Hil
da but apart from that we didn't no - I don't think I ever - we any of us were ever taught card playing. I couldn't do much with it now - but I can do a little bit - I can - I can play a game of fence and that's about all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Were there books in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Yes. We had a plenty of books. We had two if not three rows of books on that shelf - on shelves up there - on that shelf there were three shelves - one was of small war books \endash  church-hymn books and all little books and then there were the medium 
size ones and then there were the bigger books at the top. Er - many of them were - er - were books that would come out in - er - like once a week - er - magazines that were - er - kept and then bound - er - in many cases. I know that when my brother Fran
k
 worked in the Home Words office there was a copy of Home Words I remember always came - er - he used to bring home and - er - they were bound and then there was another book or two - one was young man and the other was young woman and Frank was then work
i
ng in the office with a Mr. Atkinson - I believe he was the editor of it - Frederick Atkinson. I believe he was the editor of those two books and I've asked my niece - at least my nephew who lives round Griffin because after dad died the books were divide
d
 up - different ones some had one some had the other - I don't know whether Muriel - my brother George's daughter has still got any of her dad's books but I know that he did have quite a big bookcase - some that were our - well books from home here - and 
s
ome of his own. But I know that there were some very good books - er - bound - er - church magazine was one - er - Queens Park Church Magazine was one - bound in green and that used to up on that - er - we had big books up that end and big books up that e
nd smaller ones in the middle. Then on the next shelf there would be a medium size book and then as I said the lower shelf would be the smaller books and Bibles. Church hymn books and things like this. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did you get newspapers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Er - dad's T
elegraph - dad had the Telegraph right 'til the day he died. And we kept it for years afterwards until it got yellow and I don't know what happened to it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Do your remember your mother or father reading?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Er - oh yes, yes, oh yes, they were both o
f them very - er - very good for reading and both intelligent - oh yes, wonderfully - wonderfully intelligent.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did they ever read aloud to you or to each other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Er - if there was anything - oh yes, dad would sit down and he would say mother now 
sit down come on - er - here's so and so and so and so I want to read to you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Do you remember a funeral in the family?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Well, the first funeral in the family - er - was that aunt that I was speaking of - dad's sister Sarah and then in 1916 - and
 then in 1917 was my sister's husband.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Who attended?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 We all went. We all went yes - in both the cases.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 And would you wear mourning clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh yes, yes. Oh yes, in those days, you - you were - everybody was in black then for a length 
of time - yes - for a length of time, oh yes. But I always remember
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did you draw the curtain in the house?
