\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3690258\charrsid14891508 Nellie}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508  - when she had - oh you must wear widow's weeds }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3690258\charrsid14891508 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3690258\charrsid14891508 Nellie }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
bought widow's weeds and she wore them on the day will was buried - he's buried next to my father and mother in Paddington cemetery - er - but she never wore them after - I don't know what she did with them - 
for this - with, this length of crape stuff - I know she wouldn't wear it - oh no, no Nellie didn't like anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Were you taken out visiting neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 No. Not much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Friends or relations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh friends - but we had no relati
ons much about this way - not when we were young no. Oh no, we hadn't any relations that lived in this area. Not that time - and we would go - we would go - er - now, with mother - mother would take my - er - George, my brother and I, because the eldest y
o
u see were older - look after themselves but - er - mother would take us two into the country - we had a cousin - an aunt rather - mother's - er - one of mother's sisters who lived in Welling in Hertfordshire and - er - we used to go down there and stay f
or a - a fortnight or whatever time it was. During the school holidays, oh yes, and I ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Were you fortunate with your father working on the railway - did he get free passes - did the whole family get passes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Er - no - er - you did - yes - up to 
a point. Dad had his free pass which took him and mother or he and one of the boys - er - on these long distance journeys - er - and we were entitled as a family to a cheap travel - er - well say you were going from Westland Park to the City - we had a li
t
tle voucher - a little blue voucher and whoever went first took that little tuppeny voucher up to Westland Park Station and left it there and then we would take our tuppence for our ticket and - er - Alfred would perhaps go to Moorgate Street and Frank wo
u
ld go to - er Aldersgate or - so - I would go to Baker Street - Nellie would go to - no Nellie didn't have it - George did - er - he would go wherever he was working - where we were working - oh yes - and again I remember when we were - when we were young
s
ters - mother, George and myself - er - I don't suppose the others went - at all - going from Westbourne Park to Baker Street and Baker Street down to - Rickmansworth - er - from Baker Street to Harrow was tuppence all the way with another - another - not
 
that blue ticket it was another ticket - a longer one - that you went then - er - Baker Street to Harrow and that was tuppence. Baker Street to Aylesbury I think was ninepence. We used to go out for the day always on a Bank Holiday as next Monday would be
 
- say August Bank Holiday - we'd pack up a basket of refreshments and we'd go out for the day right out into the country and then we'd - er - knock at a cottage for a pot of tea or something like that - and make a nice day out. Er - that was until of cour
s
e until we got of an age when we were able to look after ourselves and did look after ourselves and - I don't know that we went out so much then - possibly I may have gone with mother - because I think I was a little bit - er - tied to my mother's apron s
trings in a way. Er - and than.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Were you taken shopping?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh yes. Oh yes. We used to - one or the other of us always used to go with mother. Down Harrow Road for the shops - oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did you ever go out with just your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh quite likely. Quite likely. But - er -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 You told me about these outings on Bank Holidays - did you go any other times of the year - mainly always August Bank Holiday was it?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 It was mainly Bank Holiday times - er - when we would go for those little outin
gs. Er - but at - at other times as I say you would have an outing. Here - I remember going to Hastings once. Er - on an outing and falling in the sea. A man clutched hold of me and pulled me back otherwise I should have been washed out to sea. Had to sit
 - sit round an old - er - washing machine while my clothes dried.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did you ever go away for a holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Er - not apart from my - not from - er - not apart from my family - oh no. Well - er -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 You told me you went to cousins sometimes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh, well, that was when I was older - that was when we were older - that was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 In the time 1908 to 1918 do you think you went on holidays then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh yes. Yes, yes, because I was quite a woman then, oh, I was well away then. Oh yes. Well, I couldn't t
ell you exactly where I went to - it all depended. I know I went up to Aberdeen twice. Oh yes, I went to Aberdeen - to that friend of ours that I told you lived just - moved up from Kensal Rise - er - yes I went up to Aberdeen in 1905 with Maggie and - er
 - then I went again in 1914. Maggie was then up there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 And would your brothers go on holiday too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
OH YES. Oh yes, but actually apart from going on their holidays with their friends - er - perhaps to relations or perhaps to friends to the seaside somewhere they would go but apart from that they didn't - until they got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16328850 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508  I don't know that they went about a lot. Hey - you know kept each other's company and friends - with - they always had their friends coming in - into the house.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 How did you spend Saturdays? What about Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Sundays? Between 1900 and 1918? Well, mostly I - I'd - I didn't always go to church Sunday morning but I always went Sunday evening and I went to Sunday school - er - rather to the Sunday school class - yes, right the way through.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did you have different clothes on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Oh yes. Always Sunday clothes - you didn't wear your Sunday clothes on week days - oh dear no. And on Sunday school anniversary we always dressed in white - either white or something very pale - oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 So you spent Sunday afternoon in Sunday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Sunday afternoon at Sunday - in Sunday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 And Sunday evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 And Sunday evening we'd go to church - and then possibly go for a walk with whoever we came out o
f church with - friends - 'cos by that time I'd made my own friends, you see, and this one friend - Maggie - er - Miss Roberts that I spoke of a little while ago that lived here with us from 1903 - er - after George was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16328850 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508  and - er - she always used t
o come to church with me - she's a Scotch girl came from Aberdeen - and - er - she used to come to church with me with her little girl - little Queenie and - now she's got - oh I don't know how many grandchildren - half a dozen grandchildren round about -
 er - right up until 1918 - yes, and in 1917 and 18 - no - 15 to 19 - I was working in the post}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3690258\charrsid14891508  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
office - I worked in the post office - er - at Paddington station - er - letter sorting and then of course at that time we'd - we would be doing all sorts of things. Er - might even be working - yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 On Sunday yes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Not so much Sunday during the daytime but we always went in eleven o'clock Sunday evening - which had started our day. And it's just recently that I've come up against a young man - no - not
 a young man rather - I've come up against the widow of a young man that I knew who lived opposite here - George Blackhall and if his wife was listening and she heard this she'd say yes. Er - and I knitted for him before he - before he was - well long bef
ore he was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16328850 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
 - for he'd be in the army - er - I knitted for him a balaclava helmet and gloves and I think socks and during the war we used to take our knitting - our big knitting - to church with us on Sunday evening because our Minister that was then
 - think it must have been Mr Butler - don't know if it would be - er - agreed that we could knit as well as listen to what he was talking a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3690258\charrsid14891508 bout and if it was the Reverend }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Alexander Butler that I think it was - er - in 14 - 14 to 17 anyway - he certainly agreed with our work - for our doing our work for the war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did your parents go to church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh yes. Always - right until........
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 This was the Congregational church at the bottom of the road?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Church at the bottom - yes. Er - they went to church with my eldest brother - he always - he stuck to Church of England.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 How often did your parents go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Well, morning - morning and evening sometimes - oh yes, yes. Both mother and father - oh yes. And dad would go Sunday morning even if mother didn't. Yes. She was getting the Sundays dinner - oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did you go to Sunday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Yes, I went to Sunday school and then from there I became a teacher. I was teacher right until it was .....
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Were there any Sunday school outings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Yes - always. And what's more - for Sunday school at least for church work - there was what we called Christian Endeavour - we had what was termed a sunshine committee and there was twelve people in that sunshine committee - nine women - young women and t
hree men and the girls and myself - er - did the sewing part and we used to make garments all the year round and I used to cut them out - children garments - for a children}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3690258\charrsid14891508 \rquote }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 s tea that was held in the following January for after Christmas - the Christmas pa
rty for the poor little kiddies that many of them hadn't got hardly a rag to their backs. Let's see we were up to what was it - oh our sunshine committee - and our children - and we used to collect for them to give them a good tea in the January and every
 
child had a garment - we used to collect sufficient every now and again - do all sorts of things - make coconut ice to find a few coppers and sell it to the girls at work and they used to say ah Miss Morris what have we got this week. Well, I've got some 
c
oconut ice. All right, or else it'd be well now - er - er - you got your wages this afternoon? Yes. Come on I want a penny from each of you. And I'd got a friend - Alice Keeble - who was one of our girls and she'd say yes, well we're going to buy a little
 
girl a pair of shoes so we want the money to buy them with - come on. Well you've got - you've got your wages - well give me a penny out of it. And they'd all give us a penny out of it and we'd take it - I know we had a case with one little girl who wante
d
 to buy a pair of shoes because there was an outing - we'd got an outing in the June or July and mother said oh Katie can't come because she hasn't got any shoes - and that was over the other side of the - er - bridge - in the very poor - what was then th
e
 very much poorer part to what ours was considered and - er - she hadn't got any shoes and by the way don't talk too loud because behind that picture there's a big hole and the woman next door if she saw you come in would be listening to what your saying 
a
nd then she'll come and want her children to go. Well that was in the very poor - what was then the very poor part - Kensal Road. Yes. And so at all events Katie had her shoes because we got sufficient money and we took Katie to the - the little old shoe 
m
an - little shoe shop and - er - bought her shoes - but I brought away the little old rubber shoes that she'd got on when we took her - er - if I hadn't probably the leather shoes would have found their way to the pawn shop on the Monday morning - quite l
i
kely and Katie would be back into her old rubber shoes, you see, but - er - that was our work for the children and we did - we used to have a hundred to a hundred and twenty and every child had a garment - whether it was a girl or boy - my sister Nell use
d
 to make the little boys - er - knickers - because they couldn't get anybody else - nobody else'd take on the knickers that had got the flies - that had the - er - flies in - they'd make them with a little hole - yes they'd do that one but they'd do that 
pair but no, not the bigger ones and then we had a tailors shop - it's - I think it's Burtons the tailors at the present moment - it used to be Alexander}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3690258\charrsid14891508 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 s. Er - we had a tailors shop - Prince of Wales in the Harrow Road and he used to save me all the littl
e bits that we could make boys knickers of - yes - and he used to give them to us and - er - then I'd go across to Bradley }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15409448 &}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
 Perrins on the opposite side there by the Prince of Wales, that's gone now, er - and - er - when I say it's gone - yes, that's righ
t it is the - shut up - er - and I used to go and buy rolls of flannelette - striped flannelette or shrimpy pink flannelette and cut out the garments - I used to cut them out on my bed mostly - I'd say to mother in the morning - mother I've left some thin
g
s - some - er - things on my bed - don't bother about making it - I've thrown it back - don't bother because I want to cut them out when I come home. Well, I - while your getting my supper. Mother would be getting my supper and I'd go up and the old sciss
o
rs'd be going round the pattern 'cos I wanted to take these things down to the meeting, you see, for the girls and it - and I think that of the people that were with us then - actually the nine workers that were in that sunshine committee I think there's 
only two of us left. I don't think there's anybody else.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did you belong to the choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 No, no. No, I wasn't a singer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did the chapel run any temperance club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Yes. All sorts of things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Were you a member of that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Er - I went to Band of Hope. Went to Band of Hope with my brother. With George - oh yes, he and I went to Band of Hope with him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did you have any activities associated with that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Er - I don't know as I did much at that time - no. In fact - er - George did bu
t I don't know that I did - because he was that much older than I was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did you ever belong to any other club that you can think of organized by the chapel - Sunday school - Band of Hope?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Er - sunshine committee - Band of Hope - no I don't know that there was much more. Oh yes, I think we did our share of it really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Was grace said at meals in your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Who said it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 My father. Dad, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Were you taught to say prayers at night?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 And did you ever have family prayers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Er - not so much family prayers - but we - oh that's coming down the chimney - means we're going to have some rain - er - it was with mother - when we older - with her - us younger ones.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did your father take an interest in politics in their period?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Er - yes. Oh yes, yes. He didn't - er - he didn't forget his politics. He was a Liberal right the way through. Right until he died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did he have views - definite views on - did the working man have a square deal - do you 
think in those days - did your father think that the working man had a square deal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Well, I don't know - I don't know that I thought much about - it really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did your father talk about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Although - well - as a working man I suppose he did
 up to a point - I know one thing that did used to bother him that he didn't consider that the wages that the men that were on the station at the time where he was - when he was a Swiss Cottage - that the work that they did - er - not the men on the platf
o
rm - but the men in the signal box was dad's chief worry. He did not consider - I don't know what the - what the wages were at all - that was never - well of course that didn't interest me - but I know that he used to say that with the work that they did 
i
n the signal box just in the tunnel - he didn't consider they were paid sufficient for the responsibility that those men. I know it did - dad did used to bother a good deal and I think he spoke his views a good deal when he had occasion to go up to - er -
 to Baker Street to head office.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Was your mother interested in politics at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 No. No, mother was - had enough to do to look after her home - she was - her home was her little treasure.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Do you remember your father voting in a general election before 1919?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Er - before 1919 - quite possible - yes, quite possible before 1919.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 There were elections in 1900, 1906 and 1910.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Er - yes - oh he would do if there was - if it was at all possible. Yes, I don't think - and I don't think th
at he was so far invalid - er - up to 1919 and he died in 21 although he didn't go out much but I expect if there was an election he was there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Women got the vote in 1918 I think - did they - do you remember your mother voting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh well, I couldn't tell you - I don't remember mother voting - no I don't remember mother voting.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 How old were you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh I was - oh I'd be - thirty-five - I - I was thirty-five in 1915.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Do you remember voting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh I expect I did. I expect I did - I
 expect I did. Quite likely. I know that I've voted ever since - that time when I've had the chance. I remember I remember going in 1924 - I was working in 1924 - I was working at the Sudbury Hall school for girls - um - er - at Sudbury and my brother - F
r
ank - yes Frank was - on the go at the time - he was determined that I should vote - although I - I was living here but I was working there at that time and - er - he was determined that I should go so he - he sent somebody in a cab to fetch me on conditi
ons that they - er - that they would wait for me and take me back again. I got my vote and he saw to it that I - that I was going to use it too - oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Were you interested in politics at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Not a great deal - not a great deal. I had enough t
o do I think to do - to make ends meet in a way - you know - look after things and that because - um - yes by that time - 19 - 1918 - er - 1919 when - um - I was in the post office from 1915 to 1919 - and then from 1919 to 21 - no, I think I was at home h
e
re - I was at home with mother and dad. Er - no I wasn't - no I wasn't - no - er - no I did twelve months of - er - 'course during those - during that period - I did twelve er - at least from the Easter to the September - er - teaching dressmaking to unem
ployed women - up at Harleston - mm. Under the county council.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Some people felt in those days that they risked losing their jobs or their homes if they voted in a different way from their employers wanted them to - did you ever hear your father speak about this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 No, I don't think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 You don't think your father ever felt himself under this sort of pressure?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 No, I don't think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 He wouldn't be - working for the railway - would he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 No, I don't think that would be .......
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Was your father a member of a political party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Yes, he was a Liberal. Oh yes, yes. Yes, he was a Liberal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 And do you remember him working for one of the parties at an election?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Yes - Liberal - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 This is what you were telling me before, about him working for Mr .....?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Er - Mr Hornerman - yes - helping John Hornerman until - and then after that - oh yes - if there was anything on he was always with him. Oh yes, and we always - we always had the vote for so and so hanging on a bo
ard out - outside and I remember - er - they would be Conservatives - the people that lived a little further up the street named Nudick - and there were some sons there and - er - they came and took our board away - at night - mm - at night when the - whe
n the - er - the - er - elections was on. Oh yes, the feelings did run high then - at that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 But your mother wouldn't be a member of a party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 No, mother wouldn't - no, she wouldn't - no. No, no. She was indoors looking after her home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did your parents take part in any political activity other than at election time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Well, - er - for the - for the Liberal party - oh yes. Oh yes, yes, he was a staunch Liberal. All the way through - apart from elections.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 When your parents were not doing there work how did they spend their time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Well, I told you how my dad spent his time didn't I - doing that and mother'd be doing a bit of sewing. He would be doing his acrostics - yes. This'd be his book. Now then - I - I don't know whether tha
t gives a record on that front - on that back page there - no - not back page - that's - on that outer page - does that give a record of index - that's the index to it. And - er - and I - oh - as I say I've got the old boys photo but I haven't got the - u
m - I can't find this envelope. I've looked and looked and looked and I've always think that went down behind that chest of drawers and got swept up. Certainly he can - if he'd like to - if he would like to come along.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 This was your fathers hobby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 That was of course was his hobby - oh it was his hobby - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did he used to read them to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Oh yes. He used to - he'd sit by the fire in the next room. Oh he - he kept - he had everything just at his fingertips. Oh yes, all the time - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did your mother have any interests outside the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 No, not a great deal - oh no, no, not really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did she ever go out to enjoy herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh yes. She would go down to the church but - er - if there was anything on - bazaars and all things like that but not to make any - er -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Who would she go with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Oh she'd go with me - oh yes. Er - when we got older and that you see we would go together - I used to go about with her quite a lot and with dad - he would go down. In fact there'
s one in there on one of our church bazaars. Yes, well that one - er - and that was told - that was made up in - er - in leaflets and that and were sold, see, for a few coppers - oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 What time did your father get home in the evenings - do you remember - when he was working?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
When he was at work - when he was on the railway - about quarter to seven - I think he left at six - he would get home about quarter to seven.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 How many evenings a week would he spend at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 About every evening - oh yes. He was a home}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3690258\charrsid14891508 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 bird.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Unless there was something on at the church or with the Liberals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Er - more to the Liberal party or if there was anything on at the church - oh yes, if there was a concert on or anything - um - or any political meeting - you'd never find him anywhere else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did he go to any clubs like the reform club or pubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
No. No, he didn't go any clubs at all and he wasn't a man for drinking. Er - the only time when he would go - well what you could call a club - 
he belonged to the Ancient Order of Foresters and he would go over to - um - I think it was Dalston - I think his - er - club was - was it Dalston - and he would go over there and - well - pay his club money I suppose once in three months or - was it once
 a month or was it .....
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did your mother go to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 No. No, mother was - mother was just - er - that was a man's job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did your father take part in any sport?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Er - not a great deal - not a great deal - really, not in - not to go - not to go - er - out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did he attend the races?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 No - oh no. Racing was out of his category - oh yes. He didn't bet - ooh good gracious no. Oh no.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did your father and mother belong to any savings clubs like boot clubs or sick, funeral clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 We
ll, we belonged to a medical club that provided us with a doctor for a little bit - I think tuppence each I think a week - which would be about a shilling a week - er - all together - er - and that provided us with out doctor - that was paid down at the c
h
urch - oh yes - that was held at the church. But the - now what did we used to call it - sick and benefit club was it - or medical club - medical club probably - and I remember that - at that time - when that was in existence we had quite a - oh a dear ol
d
 boy as our doctor in Furnett Road - Doctor Adams - and - I don't say it's about twenty years ago now that his son - er - passed the - passed the - er - work over. I don't know what became of the son but - er - that - the doctor that I've got now is still
 
in the same house. His still at the same - in Doctor Adams - in Doctor Adams house - who is Doctor Halbein - he's not a bad sort of chap - not over - over keen on him but I know better. I met - I met one there - when I was down at Leicester that I like a 
good deal better but - er - still, Doctor Halbein's all right - if you're really ill }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3690258\charrsid14891508 he\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
s on the spot - he would be on the spot - as soon as his car - er - his daughter's car could bring him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 How did you get on with your brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Get on with them? Oh we got on all right. Yes, there was no squabbling.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Was there one you felt particularly close to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Er - no, I don't think so - no I think we were sort of - hung together. We just er - just a happy - er - old fashioned family then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 As a child who did you play with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh as a little girl - with George - my brother George - oh yes, because ........
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did you play with neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh yes. Oh after - er - well when we came to live in this house I was then ten. Oh yes,
 then I would play with my next door neighbour who was - er - that was living there then and we'd tie a piece of - we had railing along here then - and we'd tie a piece of rope on there and go right across it and there'd be about ten of you - you know, sk
ipping, skip, skip, skipping - or else you'd have your single skipping rope and you'd go up and down or you'd got a hoop and the boys had their iron hoops - oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did you play in other peoples houses much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Very little. No, I was saying - er - l
ast night or this morning - no I think it was this morning, I was talking to May when she came in - and she was sitting here and I was saying how many times that I'd been into our next door neighbours house I don't think that I've ever had above three cup
s
 of tea in that house - in 44, actually, we weren't in the habit of going into other peoples houses unless it happened to be a child's birthday - on our birthdays we did - oh yes, very few neighbours then as children from the school. But we didn't run in 
a
nd out - oh no - and as for the house next door but one here I think I've been into that house all the years that we've been - lived here - I think I've been into that house twice. I think I can have been in that house twice and - I don't think I've been 
i
nto Mr Lawton's above twice. But next door - oh yes, I do go in 34 because my friend in 34 - in the ordinary way on Saturday evenings - er - I go down to her about half past six and - er - when I'm - when I'm all right - or when she hasn't got any visitor
s
. If she has visitors or anything that happens that she's very tired and that and - er - then I don't go down. But - er - other than that I go down on Saturday evening and have a look at her telly with her husband - with May and her husband and enjoy ours
elves and have a natter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Can you remember any other games that you played other than skipping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Oh, had our skipping ropes and our hoops and - er - oh I don't know - all the rest of the children's games - er - touch and all the rest of it you know
. Or - what's the other one - rounders - rounders and we used to play rounders with the with the soft ball - one from one corner to the other sort of business.
