ou I think about going up into Shirland Road for milk - er - and when we didn't go there we used to go up to - we used to go to Sutlands first at one time and then at another time we would go to Higgins - er - and fetch milk for the skimmed milk. That's -
 
er - and that was how we came to know - um - oh, I know - was going to tell you that we had the buttercups on the one side - we used to go over to Willesden to fetch eggs with mother - to fetch eggs to sit the hens on - when we were - yes, when we used to
 have chickens on - we used to have chickens on that one side of the - of the garden - not many - about four perhaps half a dozen - not so many.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did you take part in any sports?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Not when - not a great deal. 'Cos see I wasn't all that strong and -
 until I was turned ten - oh no. And I don't know - George did and my brother Frank did - Frank was - er - well he was in - my brother Frank was one of the original - er - I'm not certain that he was the first meeting but I know that the two men whose nam
e
's familiar to me - the brothers named Wallington - who were the instigators of Queens Park Rangers and they used to hold their meetings - these two boys lived in Third Avenue - they were friends of Frank and they used to hold their little meetings in - w
e
ll what is now Green Patch - but in Lansfield Street in what was called St Jude's Hall. Not to be confused with St Jude's Institute because that's round here - that's where the club's - the - er - the Tuesday club is kept - but no - the original St Judes 
