\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang1034\langfe1033\langnp1034\insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang1034\langfe1033\langnp1034\insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 No. No. No. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
No, I never earned anything. I didn't anything until I really started work and that was - um - well ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 What was your first full time job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 My first job was - act - as full time - the othe
r was only just occasionally - but the first full time job that I had was - er - waistcoat making.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 And how did you get it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 I went to Baker Street station from Westbourne Park and from Baker Street station I walked round into High Street Marylebo
ne and I believe that the shop and house where I worked is still there. It comes on the corner of a little place like that - here's the three shops - one was Burketts the butchers - the next one was Home }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15409448 &}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508  Colonial and the next one was Krangs the bakers - 
a bakers - they had a shop there and a shop on this side of the road and then you went up George Street to a very big Catholic church - where they used to have some lovely weddings - we girls of course used to hurry out at dinner time and see these weddin
gs because the - their bride'd go in that door and she'd come out in South Street out the other door after the service - but - er - but I did about fifteen months I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 And how did you get this job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 I don't know who got me onto that job - beca
use I was supposed to go as a dressmaker or - or training as a teacher. I don't know who put me into that job at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 What exactly did you have to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Learn waistcoat making - oh yes. Oh I can .....
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Were you allowed to start sewing right away?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Oh yes. You were taught mainly - er - because this lady had her - waistcoats came already cut out you see - they would be cut out by a tailor and then - er - the apprentices had to go with a black bag - er - to put - that they put the work in - I
 don't know what they called it now - they've got a name - and - er - they had to go down to Oxford Street - there were two or three shops that our firm - our lady wo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4990543\charrsid14891508 
rked for - she was a Mrs. Groome}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508  - er - that she worked for and you had to go down - one w
ould go to one shop and one to the other - taking in what work was done - what had been done and pressed - that had to be carried on your arm in the - in this bag - then you came back with the next lot that were all - er - rolled up with the canvas and th
e lining and all that ready for you to bring back to the lady for - er - to be made up. And - er - it was all good work - one place was in Oxford Street and two I think were in Bond Street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 And you actually did some sewing though as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh yes.
 You were taught - you were taught in the sewing - oh yes, and you were taught as well as the hand sewing - because a lot of our work was hand sewn - er the finishing off at the edges was hand sewn and - er - yes - all the little stitches round the edge -
 
and then the button holes - but - oh all our buttonhole and I could tell you if you showed me a button hole now whether it's made by a dressmaker - I can tell you that's made by a dressmaker - that's not made by a tailor. Because a tailor starts - starts 
w
ork on a buttonhole in a different place to what a dressmaker does - if fact you work backwards - you go the other way round - when your working - when you're working a tailors button hole. Another thing of course - your button holes are cut out with - er
 - a clipper type of thing - er - it's got a knife in it that cuts through and it makes - pierces the hole that you work round when you're doing it - you start up there - a dressmaker starts there and works round that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Clockwise - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Er - a
 dress - a tailoress works there - she starts there and she leaves a thread of - - er - oh I've forgotten what we used to call it - like a very thin corded stuff - cord stuff - you left a thread of that and a thread of your cotton up at that and for a rea
son - then you laid this gimp - gimp - gimp - you laid your gimp round there and it come up to there - you're laying that round as you're doing your stitches.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 And you're sewing over this.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 You're working over - yes - so the gimp is inside - you l
ook at one of your husbands - you look at one of your husband's button holes on an old waistcoat and you'll find - because I expect they're still the same. You work with your gimp laying round your buttonhole and you come round there and up there - round 
t
his little hole and in that little hole had to be nine stitches - you didn't put ten - oh no - but those stitches - as you did them - you'd pull up like that - as you came that way you drew your thread tight there that the knot so to speak of your buttonh
o
le - the buttonhole stitch comes that way on a level but when you got to here you pull your stitch up - that way - and that had to have nine stitches round heaven help you if you put ten. Because she'd make you take it all undone again and then when you b
e
gan to go up to - up that side - you then keep your gimp tight round so that it forms that little hole you see - forms that little hole - if I could only see I'd make a button hole now for you to look at - then when you got to the top of you tightened tha
t
 so that that made that nice little - neat little hole - then your - you held on tight to your two pieces of gimp and you put your stitches across that and then your thread had to go down - but you cut off your gimp you see you'd finished with that and yo
u've done - you've made that tight with your thread and of course that thread had to be waxed before ever you started using it. With beeswax - I've still got a bit of beeswax here now.
