\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Yes, you've got your own bees wax and
 you had - and you had - yes, in that box I've got there - I've still got a piece of it - of that bees wax and it's not many years ago that I came up against a girl that was going into waistcoat making and I said to her have you got a still at home. No no
t
 yet she says. Well, I said, you'll want one. Now your stiletto was a piece of bone with a point - er - a rounded point at that end and this end has-got a hole in it so that - er - stiletto and your piece of wax - have you got a piece of - er - um - stour
 
tape as they called it - stour tape that went right round the edge of the waistcoat inside to keep it in form - er - you'd have a piece of stour tape - er - and that would - on one piece you'd put your bit of wax and on the other you'd put your stiletto a
n
d possibly if you were allowed you would put your small scissors but they had to be short scissors like that with round tops because of the disadvantage of having pointed scissors. Having the pointed scissors - yes - but they had to be round scissors - er
 
- one end at any rate had to be rounded so that you cut your thread dead short and dead tight. Oh they were most particular really and the hundreds of button holes that I did - er - when we were not busy - not I only - but we all - and we had to sit - um 
-
 on a platform - so that your knees were up like that you see you couldn't - you couldn't do your work working like that so therefore you had to get it so that your work was there to your level - we all - we all had a box of some sort or other - Tait suga
r box or something like - something like that more than likely. You see, and then well, if there were two of you - you would put - at night you would put all your things - your apron and your stilettos and}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4990543\charrsid14891508  things - er - all into that bo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 x and put them up ont
o the table when they were going to clear up at night. It was - but that was my first job. And I stayed there - er - about fourteen - fifteen months but .......
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 What hours did you work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Eight 'til eight. Eight in the morning 'til eight at night and four o'clock on Saturday and
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 You didn't work Sundays at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh no, no, we didn't work Sundays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 And you didn't have a half day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 No. Four o'clock Saturday and the apprentices had to scrub the work room floor before you came away so
 it was nearly five before you come away. I remember I had 'til five o'clock ...
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did you have any holidays with pay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 I - don't know whether we did or didn't because I would only be there on the one lot of holidays because as I say I packed it up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 What were you paid?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Four shillings a week. Four shillings the first year and I think I might have got to mix shillings what would be me second year - I might have got as far as that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did you feel it was a fair wage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Well, I suppose it was up to a point. Up to a point.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did you give any of the money to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Oh great Scott no - my father had to give me money to go out to pay for my doughnuts and things that we had in a dinner time because this Krangs the bakers - er 
- as I say I believe the shops still there - they used to make lovely doughnuts with the jam in all squ}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10166099\charrsid14891508 ee}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
zing out and we used to wait for these doughnuts to be finished - er - just at the time when we had our - er - bit of sandwiches or whatever we had and
 - er - those of course you sat in their kitchen and had your sandwiches and made your cup of tea or whatever you did - I've forgotten how we got on with - I suppose we did have a cup of tea - I think we all put together - yes I think we all put together 
s
ame as we did in dressmaking and made your pot of tea between you. Er - and - er - then as soon of course one o'clock you'd have - you'd have had your bit of sandwiches that you'd taken then you'd go dashing down to Krangs and come back with your bag of -
 of doughnuts - greasy doughnuts - we used to love them - I dare say they were the most indigestible things under the sun more than likely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did you get on well with the other people you worked with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Yes. With the exception of the husband of the w
oman. But I wasn't the only one. But he was a man that drank pretty heavily and he did the ironing in another room to where the work was being done. It was the wife's business but he was a painter and he gave up painting because he could earn more by doin
g
 the ironing - I think the presser had - would have left in the meantime - or else Mrs Groome herself did it - did some of the ironing - at any rate I know he came and he used to come and look out the window because if you were in - it was called Thayer S
t
reet, Marylebone - it's where High Street, Marylebone finishes there and I've forgotten what - I think that bit comes from there - Mandeville place I think it is - it comes - yes - it goes up towards Oxford Street - yes - Mandeville Place - and - er - Mar
ylebone Lane goes round the back that way - comes out at Marshall }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15409448 &}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
 Snelgroves - as far - it used to - I don't know whether it does now - I don't suppose it does now for a moment as I haven't been that way for so many years - er and he used to come to the w
indow and look over to see if the pub was open and then he'd say to his wife - Nell, I think he called her - Nellie - yes Nellie Groome - that's right because her daughter was Nellie Groome too - he'd say Nell, going for a drink. She'd say - well, shut yo
u
r iron off then - put your irons of because he'd have great big irons you know - so big - and they were irons that I think had those - er - how do you dos inside them - yes - I believe they were - 'cos as I say they were in the other room and they wouldn'
t
 be gas irons - oh I don't know they might be gas irons at that time - yes, I suppose they would be - yes - would have - er - they would have a block in that was heated by the gas - you that would be it. Er - at all events - and he'd go over at eleven o'c
l
ock and if you saw him back by one o'clock - er - well, if he was sober it was a wonder and he'd come in and he used to be very abusive to some of us girls. Mmm. Some - if he thought he would - if he just in that mood and I know that I kicked at it - oh y
e
s. I - I - come home and tell dad - tell mother and dad that I wasn't - so one day I said - I think I - I expect I got into tears and I said I'm not going to stand here and be - or sit here being insulted by that man - I'm going home - and I walked out. I
 
walked out - and I put my hat and coat on and I was going to see my dad. Why on earth I wasn't coming home here I can't tell you - but I know I went up to Swiss Cottage station to dad and told him me troubles - whether it was that I was nearer to the stat
i
on or how I got there - well I couldn't tell you now but I remember quite well going into the - into dad's booking office in tears. He said what on earths the matter with you sort of business. This man oh - he had to apologise. I know mother went the next
 day - with me - I had to go back with her and he apologised. Oh yes, he apologized for being rude and that and upsetting me.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 How did she treat you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh she was all right - Mrs - er - Mrs Groome was all right. She was a quite nice little woman - 
little dumpy sort of woman really. She was all right - but it was him - he was horrible.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 How did you feel about the work itself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 I liked it. Yes. And during the time - during the time that I was there -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10166099\charrsid14891508 
 er I knitted - or did the tric}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 ot - er crochet hook - I didn't knit rather - I crocheted the two fronts of a b}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10166099\charrsid14891508 
lack waistcoat - I did the trico}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 t part of it and er - when I got to the pockets the - er - I think it was the machine - as far as I remember her name was Alice - she did that part for me or
 showed me how to finish off the little bit of pocket here - the braid that - of course it was braided you see at the edge and then it was spotted with blue silk - this black waistcoat - it was lined at the back with flannel - I think that was the object 
o
f it 'cos dad had been ill and I think that was the object that he should have this woolen waistcoat. You see. And - er - 'cos I know he had to wear it - I was going to say night and day pretty well - er - he didn't leave it off at all during summer time 
and - er - at least unless it got really very hot and that but I know it was his - his waistcoat was looked upon as a little bit of gold dust}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10166099\charrsid14891508  really. But these little blue C}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 hinese silk dots that I - I did all the dotting - I know Alice set the machine - set
 me going as to how to do it having done the - er - crocheting part - I did all the crocheting I know - with her help - she put me right as to how to do or - er - leave off so many stitches when you were making the arms and all that part - er - the front 
part. And then it was - would be lined with - er - black - um - with flannel cloth - oh it was a beautiful thing time it was finished - in - in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 What was the next job you had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Er - after that I think I stayed home for all the winter and - er - after that I would go into dressmaking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did you start an apprenticeship again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Er - not actually an apprenticeship. Not - er - I wasn't a bound apprentice like my sister. No, I - well, I could sew - I - I couldn't tell you exactly - no - I was what then they would call an improver.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 How did you get this second job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
That I couldn't tell you. Out of the Indicator I expect. More than that - the local paper that used to be a ha'penny, that - that came here. You'd - you'd get the Indicator. I expect that's how I got my next - oh several jobs - one after the other.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 And what did you do in these dressmaking jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh, that would be as an improver and then you got to be as an assistant and then um - you'd leave that job if you 
thought you could better yourself and - er - get another one and no - no - er - queries as to what can you do and what can't you do - er - you were put to it and if you could do it well you did it. If you didn't well you were told at the end of the week t
hat you weren't any good. I don't think I ever come to that stage - I think I managed to carry on.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 What were your hours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 In dressmaking? Oh I don't think we were quite so late as that - not - not the eight to eight. No - and think the first one 
that I did in dressmaking actually as I say as an improver was - um - down by Royal Cak station where it's all now chopped up - all that bit - somewhere down there. Down by Royal Cak station - I don't know how long I was there - about six months I expect.
 
I did have a record years ago of all the jobs I did and how long I stayed there - like my dad did. I expect it was he that set me off doing it - er - um - really, in the first place, but - um - er - I don't know what became of it - goodness knows. But wha
t
 I did - the job that I did keep then after those one or two odd little places was - um - in - 1900 - mm - well I'd be then twenty wouldn't I - I'd be - yes - I'd be about twenty - er - of a lady who was a dressmaker - this was dressmaking but it wasn't i
n
 that sense - er - um - she was working for Peter Robinsons - they would have a model come from Paris and it would come to this lady - to Miss Rice - and - er - er - the one place she was - we were working at that I worked with her - one was over the corn
e
r of Second Avenue - she worked there. Then from there we moved to - er - Fernhead Road - just at the junction of the Prince of Wales - the first shop that was there. At least a private house up there and the work used to come from Peter Robinsons who'd h
ave one of these - er - m}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10166099\charrsid14891508 odels gowns that had come from P}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
aris - probably in black - and - er - you would copy it. You had all the - er - instructions as to - well you'd got to work out how many frills there were and how deep they were and how far apart they
 were - all the rest of it. I remember one frock being made. Er - one of these models and it had seven frills and they came up - that one came up round that - er - from the bottom and then the other one came a little further along - the other one came a l
i
ttle further along and there were seven frills - because I know that in 1903 - haven't got a photo of mother taken in that frock - but my sister and I made mother a frock in blue - royal blue - er - crepey sort of stuff but instead of having the seven fri
l
ls she had five frills - there were three along the bottom and then there was the two extra that were put in that made the flow of the long dress as it dangled down onto the ground. Was for my brother George's wedding - yes and - always remember that. Mot
h
ers dress - oh she had a copy of a Paris model - mm. And if you had that dress it would come - I think on a Thursday morning and you'd - 'cos I know I used to stay with Miss Rice to help work it out - I don't know why - why I was a bit of a favourite - bu
t
 I used to stay with her and we'd work this - er - out - how many - how far this and you'd get your - I think you had a sketch came - mm - I think there was a sketch came with the dress that you had to copy - quite probable. And then you used to have to g
e
t all out to the different measurements. And then - then the - er - van from Peter Robinsons would come back the next day - the next day - and collect up that model - but he would bring with him - er - perhaps two rolls of black and then of course there w
a
s silk linings you see or whatever lining it had - then perhaps then a roll - a roll of black and a roll of coloured or a roll of white. You see. And - er - then of course - in your workroom - oh we had about five or six of us there - working for Miss Ric
e
 - then you'd set to and - I used to help her cut them out and then I used to do a good part of the machining - while the others pinned them on and tacked them on and all the rest of it. Er - the frills - in the making. Now they would be skirts - they wou
l
dn't be bodice parts - they would be skirts because you only did skirts - but the rights of any firms - er - I - was a little bit of a blank to me really - I was - and I do remember working on these frills and I know that it was Miss Rice that I worked wi
th - er - would be from 1900 then - George was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16328850 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
 in 1903 and I think I left Miss Rice - I don't know why - it wasn't because of the work - I don't know why I left her in 1904 - and I know I went down to Westbourne Grove.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 How much were you paid by Miss Rice?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh, I couldn't tell you - about twelve shillings I think - ten or twelve shilling.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Would you feel this was a fair wage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh yes it was a fair wage as things were then - at - the work that you were doing Of course I ........
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Do you remember if you gave any to your mother?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh I expect I did - I expect I gave her some. But I suppose what I gave her she gave me back more than likely. Quite possible.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 How did you get on with the other people you worked with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh a
ll right. Yes. I don't know that I ever had any trouble with anyone that I worked with. And there's one old lady - if she's still alive - she was in - er - St Alfreds hospital a year or two ago and her niece lives down the street now and I haven't seen Ka
therine for a long time now - no - to know whether her aunts still alive - that used to work with me in that workroom - er - putting these frills and that on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 How did you feel about the work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Well, it was very at - er - very touchy type of work -
 you'd got to be so very particular with it. And - er - that you didn't dare do anything out of place - I know that - I know there's a good deal of worry. Really. I liked the work and that - oh yes. Then I went after - I don't know why - whether I left Mi
s
s Rice myself or whether it was that she closed down - er - for doing Peter Robinson I seem to think it was that - for doing that type of work. I know she was a single woman - er - she used to go to Doctor Clifford's church - she was just her and her moth
e
r that lived there in this house in Fernhead Road and - er - but - I don't remember quite - giving the job up - I'm almost sure I didn't give the job up - and - myself - not for any reason that way - but I know that I went after there - after that - I wen
t
 to - er - Wallace Tailors which was an ordinary dressmakers - er - in er - Westbourne Grove - where we did - some was made and some part was altered work - things that were bought in the shop - and - er - they came up to us to be altered to fit to the pe
r
son that they were wanted for. And - er - the - there was the two shops. One was a milliners - his wife ran the milliners and the husband ran the other shop - this - er - this dressmakers place. But I know we did a lot of quite nice work there - than I st
ayed with them until our fitter gave up - in 1909 - yes - 'cos I'd be five years with - five - yes - and four - 1904 - well between four and five possibly - er - to 1909 when I went to Derry and Thomas. And I went to Derry and Thoms ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 What hours did you work at this last job - do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Well, I think we did leave there at seven - I think we got to the stage that our times would be then - no - it would be about half past eight - I think we got in at half past eight and - er - and - half pa
st eight and I think we left at seven - by that - mm - by that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Then you worked Saturdays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Um - yes - I expect we worked Saturdays a bit - but I think the times that come - according to the factory act or something - I think we didn't work after about two o'clock - about two o'clock I think. And I think ....
