\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Er - yes. I had - er - fourteen - fourteen to start with 
and then I got to fifteen - I got a shilling and I don't think I got to the sixteen - in fact I know I hadn't - no - because Julia Harmond only had sixteen and she was the - er - Edie and Julia Harmond were sisters and they had - er - sixteen, because the
 
first skirt hand and her sister - don't know what her sister had as the assistant - but the first skirt hand - er - I think she did have eighteen or a pound - she had - er - it was the fact that when it came to 1914 the war started and between there and 1
9
 - beginning of 1915 half of us were - er - on the dressmaking part - doing what bit of dressmaking came in and the other half of us - er - according to your length of service - the other half of us were over in the other side of the work room and we were
 
doing - er - piece work - making - making - er - oh cut - er - the second hand would cut out the capes - nurses capes and you stitched them up - and we had one machine between about six of us that you had to be - er - pinning your seam up while somebody e
