\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 You were like a welfare position more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
Er - well - yes - er - what we would call - what we would call section leaders. We were called section leaders you see, and you were in charge of so many women - perhaps about twenty all together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 What hours did you work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Well, 
um - we had four duties - one would be about eight or nine in the morning 'til about five in the afternoon - was it half past seven - half past four - I think that was our early duty - this week. Then we would get the - that would be our day turn - then a
f
ter that you would get one - the next one you would have would be - er - half past three in the afternoon 'til eleven o'clock at night. Then you came - when you came out from that Post Office you had to watch out that Gerry wasn't dropping a few bombs dow
n
 overhead. Um - then - er - then after the eleven o'clock one - the next one then would be the midnight - er - what time did we go on midnight - eleven o'clock - yes eleven at night to six o'clock in the morning - yes, course it was. We had one at midnigh
t - er - night duty as they called it and then - two of eleven o'clocks and the one of - er - a day duty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did you have any holidays with pay from there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh yes, oh yes, you did. Oh yes, well you had - your holiday time - yes. But I don't think th
ere was a lot of holidays - er - I don't think that there were a lot of holidays thought about really - not during the war. Oh no, no, no, we were ......
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Do you remember what you were paid?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 What were we paid? Yes. When we first started - that fi
rst week we had twenty-four shillings - well, that twenty-four instead of my thirteen - oh - I thought I was quids in all together. And - er - then we went right out onto the work - the following week - and really started work - we had twenty - twenty - s
even shillings. But once we got - what rises we had I couldn't tell you. I don't think there was much in those.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 When you were section leader were you paid more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Er - I think I must have done - I'm not quite sure. I'm not quite sure whether we wer
e. If you were it was only a matter of a couple of shillings but I'm not quite sure that we did have any extra - I think it was merely the fact that you were section leaders over those girls.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 And did you think that this was a fair wage that you were getting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh, yes, at those time - oh yes, yes, it was quite a good wage.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Did you give some of this to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh, I expect so. Yes. I expect I did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 And what would she spend it on? Have you any idea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh no. I couldn't tell y
ou. I suppose it went in the kitty more than likely. Or if there was anything I wanted or dad would say look here what about spare shoes, you know, something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 How did you get on with the other people you worked with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Very well. There w
as only one person - er - a young man that came back invalided that was a bit touchy with me and he was going out with one of the girls that was working in the office and he was a bit - I couldn't tell you why - but he was the cause of me having a very na
s
ty accident. This young man - yes. Have you ever been in a sorting office - Post Office sorting office - well, I don't know what they've got now, but we had seats swung round underneath - it would be here and it would swing right round and underneath you 
s
ee, and when you wanted to sit down you'd pull that seat out to there and sit you see. But - as you were wanting to get to that end your chair - your seat would just automatically move a little you see, so if you were sitting here, if you were sitting her
e
 - er - as a fixture well you couldn't get to that side and you couldn't get to that side. It would go in a half circle - mm. And this young man put - I think I'd had to put - Ida Sammons was the girl that he was going out with - and she was one of my gir
l
s and she was quite a - I was all right with her - but I think I had occasion to pull her up - er - some neglect of something - I think it was time upstairs that she'd had - er - wanting to meet him - I think that was it - there was something connected wi
t
h this young man I know - and he thought he'd have his own back on me and - so when we're sitting very quietly there - er - one morning - it was a morning time we was on duty - 'cos I know I had to come home - I was home for three weeks after that - er - 
a
t least I had to be under the doctor for three weeks after - and he pulled the seat away from me. And that threw me right on the bottom of my back. He came - you see - collecting up letters in the course of his work - he just had his own back. Pulled the 
s
eat away from me - so I went down wallop - I know they had to carry - take me upstairs and send for the doctor. He got suspended - he got suspended - for a week or two - mm - he was pulled up and he said of course it was an accident - that I got up too qu
i
ck or something of that. I'm thinking of your time. Yes, so he - so that was - er - he pulled - clean away from me and - er - sat me down on the floor you see. And as I say - er - had to get the doctor - I was home then - I think I was home three weeks af
ter that accident but - er - I'm afraid - I'm afraid I never forgave him for it - but still - got over it in the finish.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 How did you feel about the work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 Oh the work was all right. I didn't mind that work at all. We used to enjoy ourselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8795008 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 How did your employer treat you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5453887 HB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6820256\charrsid14891508 
What Paddington - Paddington Post Office? Oh well, we were well looked after - oh yes. Because - er - our - at the Christmas time of course we were all very busy - oh yes - lines and lines - sacks of letters and that 
you know all had to go through and we - er - we were - um - allowed to go on the - having sorted the letters we were then put on to - um - what did they call them - bays - on to a bay and which would be - one of mine was Windsor Road - for one length of t
i
me and you had to collect up - you got all your letters for Windsor proper here and then the others would be - well, Twyford, Abingdon - er - Shillingford - or course I - Wallingford and all that - all that - yes, because my was - the one bay that I was o
n
. And then of course you had to go to the registry office - er - behind the wire - the man behind - me hand behind the wire for registered letters that had to go into your bag and everything had to be signed for before you had it - and before oh yes, and 
before you but it into the bag - it had to go in - into a little green bag and before you tied up the - er - sack and punched the - er - the little lead seal - punched that - that fastened your bag - oh yes.
